  "response_text": "The mean household risk attitude values begin near 0.0 at the start of the simulation and exhibit a rapid increase, reaching a range between approximately 0.2 and 0.8 by the 30th time step. Following this initial growth phase, the metrics largely stabilize with minor fluctuations until around the 40th time step. A significant divergence occurs shortly after the 40th time step, where a portion of the trajectories sharply declines, dropping into negative values by the 60th time step, while other trajectories remain elevated, stabilizing above 0.6. By the final time step at 100, the data has bifurcated into distinct clusters: a lower group hovering around -0.2 to 0.0 and an upper group maintaining values between 0.6 and 0.8. This behavior suggests that while initial uncertainty leads to a general increase in risk tolerance, external factors or internal feedback mechanisms later trigger a split in household strategies, with some agents becoming risk-averse and others remaining risk-tolerant."
}

